    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-10-01T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-10-01T15:00:00-05:00" n="215"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d215">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1032</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Unsigned telegram from <gloss type="from"
                            >Constantinople</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">British Embassy</gloss>
                        at Washington, September 30, 1914</hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>[<hi rend="italic">Left at the Department of State by the British
                        Ambassador</hi>, <lb/>
                    <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-10-01T15:00:00">
                        <hi rend="italic">October 1, 1914, 3 p.m.</hi>
                    </date>]</dateline>
                <p>There seems to be good reason to fear that in the general excitement which
                    prevails in this part of the world, if war breaks out now Christians in Turkey
                    will be in danger especially in outlying parts of the Empire, for instance,
                    missionaries.</p>
                <p>The present coal supplies will last the Turkish Fleet about six weeks. If the
                    Turks get more coal, they will be encouraged to go to war. Their only source of
                    supply is from the United States. Would it not be possible to put some
                    difficulties in the way of this supply which will probably be carried out
                    through British tramp steamers from American ports?</p>
            </div>
        </body>
